Misha is currently taking a Complexity Theory exam, but he seems to have forgotten a lot of the material! In the question, he is asked to fill in the following boxes with $\subseteq$ and $\subsetneq$ to identify the relationship between different complexity classes: $$\mathsf{NL}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\ \mathsf{P}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\ \mathsf{NP}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\ \mathsf{PH}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\ \mathsf{PSPACE}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\ \mathsf {EXP}$$and $$\mathsf{coNL}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\ \mathsf{P}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\ \mathsf{coNP}\  box{\phantom{tt}}\ \mathsf{PH}$$Luckily, he remembers that $\mathsf{P} 
eq \mathsf{EXP}$, $\mathsf{NL} 
eq \mathsf{PSPACE}$, $\mathsf{coNL} 
eq \mathsf{PSPACE}$, and $\mathsf{NP} 
eq \mathsf{coNP}\implies \mathsf{P}
eq \mathsf{NP} \land \mathsf{P}
eq \mathsf{coNP}$. How many ways are there for him to fill in the boxes so as not to contradict what he remembers?
